hich will administer financial support to cover additional supported </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:normal">accommodation costs under Universal Credit. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#d14414; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Local Housing Allowance </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.49pt; padding-left:2.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Young single people who are subject to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Shared Accommodation Rate (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">SAR</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> are particularly likely to face probl</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ems in accessing affordable accommodation. Mystery shopper research in three local authorities across England showed that only 1.5% (66) of the 4360 shared properties advertised were in fact accessible to SAR recipients. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">In theory, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">13% had been affordable, but only 1.5% were both affordable and had landlords willing to let to young people on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Housing B</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">enefit.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.49pt; padding-left:2.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">The recent changes to the age threshold for the SAR has made this situation even worse. Raising the threshold to 35 in Januar</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">y 2012 has brought thousands more people into the shared accommodation market, but this has not been matched by any initiatives to increase supply, thus inevitably driving up prices. The change has brought an estimated 62,500 additional claimants into the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">SAR, 11,780 in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> alone</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> This particularly disadvantages under 25s as many landlords prefer to avoid renting to young people as they perceive them to be riskier tenants. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.49pt; padding-left:2.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Despite the hope that the reduction in LHA rates would push rents downwards, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">this has not been the case. Department for Work and Pensions research has found that, in the majority of cases, the difference between LHA payment and rent levels is being made up by tenants rather than landlords through reductions in rent</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> Worryingly the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> full impact of this is yet to be fully seen, with landlords indicating that, rather than pursue evictions if tenants fall into arrears, they will instead not renew tenancies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> Further research has found that a substantial number of landlords who currently</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> rent to LHA recipients say they are likely to scale back renting to this group in future because of increased concerns about rent arrears.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.49pt; padding-left:2.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">This tough and competitive environment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">not only </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">leaves vulnerable young people</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> with extremely limited options</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">is making it difficult for supported accommodation providers to facilitate move on from services. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">It has long been the case that hostel provision has filled up </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">with people waiting to access independent housing, thus preventing others from accessing support</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ed provision</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">. This problem </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">known as ‘bed blocking’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> is in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> part</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> caused by a lack of affordable accommodation accessible to those on LHA and high up front costs of entering the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Private Rented Sector (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">PRS</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.49pt; padding-left:2.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Research from Cambridge University, commissioned by</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> Centrepoint</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> su</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ggests an additional </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">15,670 units </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">of emergency and supported accommodation are required to avoid turning away young people who are without suitable accommodation and who may be street homeless, sofa-surfing or staying in other temporary </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">forms of accommodation.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> Whilst this is a substantial number if there </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">was an adequate supply of independent accommodation for young people to move on to, this shortfall would reduce to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">6,509</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">places.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">We are concerned that the combination of welfare reforms </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">will continue to limit move on options preventing young people from moving forward with their lives and further intensifying the problem of ‘bed blocking’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#d14414; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Direct payment of housing costs to claimants </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">One of the main </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">features</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">of U</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">niversal </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">redit will be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> direct payment of housing costs to claimants. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Although national roll out will affect large numbers of vulnerable people the impact</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> of this </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">has never been </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">robustly</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> tested – trials of direct payments </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">have excluded vulnerable groups including those in sup</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ported housing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">While there is no</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> formal </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">, yet</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">experience</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> of the support needs and existing debt levels of homeless young people suggests that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> the introduction of direct payments could be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">very problematic. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Forthcoming research from Centrepo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">int has found that a significant number of young people already have difficulty in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">keeping up with </s