pan style="color:#d14414; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Whilst we were </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">please</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> to see the Department state its intent to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> exclude </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">supported accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the scope of Universal Credit we are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">extremely </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">concerned </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">about the narrow ‘exempt accommodation’ definition that properties will ne</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ed to meet. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">This definition, originally drawn up in 1996, is out of date and does not reflect changes in commissioning arrangements that have occurred in the intervening years, particularly since the introduction of Supporting People in 2003.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">To meet th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">e definition, the support provider must have a legal interest in the land</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">(i.e. be the owner or legal leaseholder) or provide support on the landlord’s behalf. However, Supporting People contracts now tend to be directly between the local authority and sup</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">port provider, meaning that properties are not technically ‘exempt’ unless that support provider also owns or leases the property.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">It is important to stress that these different set ups can provide exactly the same models of service and support to tenan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ts. The only difference is that the housing management processes have been set up in different ways in terms of the division of legal responsibilities between </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the landlord and the support provider. This division does not impact on the overall cost of the s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ervice, only how this is divided between the parties involved. This means that two services</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> on the same street</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> that provide exactly the same service could be treated differently just because of how the housing management responsibilities were divided up in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> the contract.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">We are therefore extremely concerned that only some services technically meet the ‘exempt’ definition and can be sure that their tenants will be able to receive higher rates of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Housing B</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">enefit to meet their accommodation costs.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> This inconsistent approach to supporting vulnerable people could lead some to be disadvantaged, purely as a result of whether their support provider has a legal interest in the property. If some services are no longer treated as exempt, and therefore unab</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">le to recoup rents that reflect higher costs of delivering supported accommodation that are recognised by current practice</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">we fear that this could make large numbers of homelessness services financially unviable</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Ministers have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">indicated their willingness</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">address</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">prob</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">lem with </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the definition </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">but given the severity of the situation, we believe it is important to look at this as a matter o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> urgency</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">primary concern </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">remains</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> the publishing of an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">exempt accommodation definition that rectif</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ies </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the current</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> situation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">there remains uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> too</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> about future systems</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> for administering</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> financial support. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">The Department have</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> indicated it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">want</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> to meet the housing costs of supported housing through a new localised system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">owever, there is very little detail as to what a new localised system will look like once Universal Credit has been rolled out and housing benefit offices are closed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Incorrect</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> design and implementation of local </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> could pose significant risks to providers. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">It is essential </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">adequate funding is allocated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">and ring-fenced by the Department</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> for the purposes of meeting these additional costs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Without </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ring-fencing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">funding could be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">used to cover other budget shortfalls</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">across </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">hard pressed local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> - as has been the case with S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">upporting</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> P</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">eople funding. Ongoing uncertainty makes </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">very difficult for providers to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">develop long-term </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">plan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">s a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">nd pursue innovative service delivery models. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#d14414; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#d14414; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Reforms to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">LHA </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">have increased competition for properties in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">PRS</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">, making it even harder for young people to secure affordable accommodation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">The lack of suitable acc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ommodation is resulting in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">young people </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">being unable </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> make </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the step to independent living instead s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">taying in supported accommodation despite a readiness to move on. This bed blocking is limiting providers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> ability to meet the demands on its </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">service and leaving</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> other</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> homeless young people without access to the support they need. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">Alternative payment arr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">angements could potentially support a significant number of young people</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> keep up with rent payments. However, g</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">iven the reluctance of many young people to volunteer information that may help them qualify for</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> APA </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">it is essential that the Department </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">provides detail</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> how third parties will be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">drawn upon </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">to ascertain a claimant</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> eligibility for an alternate arrangement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">We appreciate that the Department did not intend for the definition of exempt acco</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">mmodation to cause the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">problems it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">create </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">and note the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">willingness to find a workable solution. Howev</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">er, given the risk this poses</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">the sector and vulnerable people</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt"> we are concerned at the slow progress in finding a solution. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic">25 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt"> Sanders, B., Teixeira, L., </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">No room available: study of the availability of shared accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">(2012). Available at: http://www.crisis.org.uk/data/files/publications/1212%20No%20room%20available.pdf [Acce</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">ssed 14 September </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">2013] </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">Department for Work and Pensions, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Housing Benefit equality impact assessment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">(August 2011). Available at </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/175083/eia-hb-shared-accommodation-age-threshold.pdf.pdf [Accessed 8 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">Septemb</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">er </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">2013] </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span>